ave been a very precise storm when I needed one, Neris, a gust that arrives as if it were an accident rehearsed by fate. Remember that sometimes rescuing a law from itself requires a hand no one sees and a silence that can be sworn only to oneself. Decide whether you want gratitude or righteousness, and accept the price, because you cannot eat both and I have brokers who will eat either if you leave them unattended.\"\n        },\n        {\n          \"speaker\": \"Neris Quay\",\n          \"lines\": \"Flames remember the fingers that set them alight, and if I listen closely, I can hear the echo in the hiss where resin meets wick. I will watch the lamps, and if one burns backward, I will make sure it does not take the city with it, even if I must burn my own sleeve to smother it. The river does not love liars, even when they float, and I have seen what a lie looks like when it finally sinks and drags a barge of names down with it. If I must choose between a truth that shames and a silence that stains, I will choose the truth and learn to wash. And if a hand reaches to spill saffron across the tally cords, my arrow will pin that hand to the law long enough for the count to stand upright.\"\n        }\n      ],\n      \"choices\": [\n        {\n          \"id\": \"C1\",\n          \"title\": \"Expose the counterfeit publicly to Clerk-Marshal Ista Brine\",\n          \"text\": \"You step from the gallery as the bell begins its iron prayer and walk across the river-stone map, each footfall a pebble dropped into circles of attention. The heat of the lamp tray prickles your knuckles as you lift the forged moon-flame with tongs, and you keep your breath shallow so the resin cannot hear your heartbeat. Voices sharpen into spear points as you set the lamp on Ista Brine’s desk and speak plainly about backward-burning resin and the hands that carried it. You do not name suspects without proof, but you paint the path of the lamp with words that glint like pins in a map, markin